	<div class="entry-content">
		<p><figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_10306" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10306" style="width: 600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="10306" data-permalink="https://evelyngeorneys.com/2023/01/29/geology-word-of-the-week-m-is-for-mica/pxl_20230125_023454492/" data-orig-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1920" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;1.73&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Pixel 6a&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1674650094&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;4.38&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;249&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.010006&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;latitude&quot;:&quot;-27.530758333333&quot;,&quot;longitude&quot;:&quot;152.96265&quot;}" data-image-title="PXL_20230125_023454492" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;A picture of muscovite, a common mica mineral. Picture by myself.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg?w=1024" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-10306" src="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="450" srcset="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg?w=600&amp;h=450 600w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg?w=1200&amp;h=900 1200w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg?w=150&amp;h=113 150w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg?w=300&amp;h=225 300w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg?w=768&amp;h=576 768w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/73f00-pxl_20230125_023454492-scaled-1.jpg?w=1024&amp;h=768 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-10306" class="wp-caption-text">A picture of muscovite, a common mica mineral. Picture by myself.</figcaption></figure></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>def. <strong>Mica</strong>:</p>
<p>A term used to describe a group of minerals that form in flat layers (or sheets) and have a vitreous or pearly <a href="https://evelyngeorneys.com/2023/01/15/geology-word-of-the-week-l-is-for-luster/">luster</a> (they are shiny!). Micas are <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Category:Phyllosilicates">phyllosilicate</a> minerals, also known as &#8220;sheet silicate&#8221; minerals. Micas are common rock-forming minerals, although some varieties are harder to find than others. Micas come in many different colors. Common mica minerals include <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muscovite">muscovite </a>(clear), <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biotite">biotite</a>(black), and <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phlogopite">phlogopite </a>(dark brown). The different colors of mica can be explained by their large range of chemical compositions. Micas always contain silica and often contain elements such as potassium, sodium, or calcium (in one structural position) and aluminum, magnesium, or iron (in another structural position). More rarely, other elements can fill these structural positions, which can lead to some amazing color variations. For example, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lepidolite">lepidolite</a> contains lithium and can be purple or pink in color. As another example, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fuchsite">fuchsite</a> contains chromium and is bright green in color. Micas are soft minerals, generally about 2.5-3 on the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohs_scale">Mohs hardness scale</a>.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Mica is one of my favorite minerals. Who doesn&#8217;t love a shiny mineral that comes in a variety of fun colors?</p>
<p>The photograph above shows a large piece of muscovite that I have in my personal rock collection. I collected it from a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pegmatite">pegmatite</a>, a rock that commonly contains large crystals.</p>
<p>I recently saw some gorgeous specimens of mica when I visited the <a href="https://mmgerdau.org.br/">Museum of Mines and Metal</a> in Belo Horizonte, Brazil. Below are some pictures of the mica specimens on display at the museum. Enjoy!</p>
<p><figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_10308" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10308" style="width: 600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="10308" data-permalink="https://evelyngeorneys.com/2023/01/29/geology-word-of-the-week-m-is-for-mica/pxl_20230129_175719234/" data-orig-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/5cace-pxl_20230129_175719234-scaled-1.jpg" data-orig-size="2560,1920" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;1.73&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;Pixel 6a&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;1675004239&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;4.38&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;158&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0.008338&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;,&quot;latitude&quot;:&quot;-19.9318&quot;,&quot;longitude&quot;:&quot;-43.938719444444&quot;}" data-image-title="PXL_20230129_175719234" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;A beautiful sample of muscovite. Picture by myself. &lt;/p&gt;
