<p>Several years ago, I used to write a &#8220;Geology Word of the Week&#8221; post in which I selected a word used by geologists, wrote a definition of the word, and wrote up a post with some information and pictures related to the word. I went through the alphabet in order twice, writing about words starting with letters from A to Z, and then I started a third run through the alphabet, stopping at my last post <a href="https://evelyngeorneys.wordpress.com/2015/01/18/geology-word-week-j-jasper/">J is for Jasper</a> back in 2015. Many people enjoyed my geology word posts, but eventually life became too busy for me to keep up the posts. Since 2015 I&#8217;ve obtained an M.Sc. degree in Carbon Management, moved countries, changed jobs twice, and had a child&#8230; all while working full-time during a global pandemic! Life is still very busy, but it isn&#8217;t quite as busy as it used to be.</p>
<p>For awhile, I&#8217;ve been thinking about reviving my weekly geology word posts&#8230; and I&#8217;ve decided that this year I will do so! I will do my best to post about a geology word every week. I may keep some of the posts a bit shorter than I used to, but I think they will still be informative.</p>
<p>Without further ado, here is the first word for 2023&#8230;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>def. <strong>Karst</strong>:</p>
<p>A type of topography or landscape characterized by the dissolution of soluble rocks, such as limestone and dolomite. The dissolution of the rocks leads to the formation of landforms such as sinkholes, caves, and springs. Water is often stored underground in karst landscapes, and thus they can form aquifers that provide sources of water for humans and animals. The sinkholes that form in karst environments are geological hazards that must be monitored and managed.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Here is a great figure showing some typical features of a karst landscape:</p>
<p><figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_10238" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10238" style="width: 797px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="10238" data-permalink="https://evelyngeorneys.com/2023/01/06/geology-word-of-the-week-k-is-for-karst/karst-landforms/" data-orig-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/b4e80-karst-landforms.png" data-orig-size="797,491" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="karst landforms" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Features of a karst landscape. Figure source: https://www.gsi.ie/en-ie/programmes-and-projects/groundwater/activities/understanding-irish-karst/karst-landforms/Pages/default.aspx&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/b4e80-karst-landforms.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/b4e80-karst-landforms.png?w=797" loading="lazy" class="size-full wp-image-10238" src="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/b4e80-karst-landforms.png" alt="" width="797" height="491" srcset="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/b4e80-karst-landforms.png 797w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/b4e80-karst-landforms.png?w=150&amp;h=92 150w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/b4e80-karst-landforms.png?w=300&amp;h=185 300w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/b4e80-karst-landforms.png?w=768&amp;h=473 768w" sizes="(max-width: 797px) 100vw, 797px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-10238" class="wp-caption-text">Features of a karst landscape. Figure source: <a href="https://www.gsi.ie/en-ie/programmes-and-projects/groundwater/activities/understanding-irish-karst/karst-landforms/Pages/default.aspx" rel="nofollow">https://www.gsi.ie/en-ie/programmes-and-projects/groundwater/activities/understanding-irish-karst/karst-landforms/Pages/default.aspx</a></figcaption></figure></p>
<p>Most karst landscapes form in carbonate rocks, such as <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Limestone">limestone</a> or <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dolomite_(rock)">dolomite</a>. In these rocks, the dissolution is caused by weak <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carbonic_acid">carbonic acid</a> that forms when rainwater picks up carbon dioxide from the atmosphere and soil. In the open spaces of caves that form underground, the carbon dioxide in the water can be released, which causes the formation of <a href="https://evelyngeorneys.wordpress.com/2011/03/09/geology-word-of-the-week-s-is-for-speleothem/">speleothems</a>, such as stalactites and stalagmites. If you&#8217;ve ever been in a cave with stalactites and stalagmites, then you&#8217;ve been in a karst landscape.</p>
<p>Below are a few pictures from <a href="https://howecaverns.com/">Howe Caverns,</a> a limestone cave in New York State that I recently visited with my family. You can visit an underground lake in this cave &#8211; and you can even take a boat ride on the lake! If you want to see a karst landscape up close, then I recommend a visit to Howe Caverns or another cave system.</p>
<p><figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_10243" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10243" style="width: 600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="10243" data-permalink="https://evelyngeorneys.com/2023/01/06/geology-word-of-the-week-k-is-for-karst/facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734/" data-orig-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg" data-orig-size="960,720" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Stalactites forming at Howe Caverns, New York State. Picture by myself. &lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg?w=300" data-large-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg?w=960" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-10243" src="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="450" srcset="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg?w=600&amp;h=450 600w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg?w=150&amp;h=113 150w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg?w=300&amp;h=225 300w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg?w=768&amp;h=576 768w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e41e9-facebook_1672969719319_7016943585621723734.jpg 960w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-10243" class="wp-caption-text">Stalactites forming at Howe Caverns, New York State. Picture by myself.</figcaption></figure></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_10245" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10245" style="width: 600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="10245" data-permalink="https://evelyngeorneys.com/2023/01/06/geology-word-of-the-week-k-is-for-karst/facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963/" data-orig-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e25a1-facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963.jpg" data-orig-size="704,960" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="&lt;p&gt;Speleothems and an underground river at Howes Caverns, New York State. Picture by myself.&lt;/p&gt;
" data-medium-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e25a1-facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963.jpg?w=220" data-large-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e25a1-facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963.jpg?w=704" loading="lazy" class="wp-image-10245" src="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e25a1-facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="818" srcset="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e25a1-facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963.jpg?w=600&amp;h=818 600w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e25a1-facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963.jpg?w=110&amp;h=150 110w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e25a1-facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963.jpg?w=220&amp;h=300 220w, https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e25a1-facebook_1672969728801_7016943625390245963.jpg 704w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /><figcaption id="caption-attachment-10245" class="wp-caption-text">Speleothems and other cave rocks reflected in an underground river at Howes Caverns, New York State. Picture by myself.</figcaption></figure></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><figure data-shortcode="caption" id="attachment_10246" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-10246" style="width: 600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img data-attachment-id="10246" data-permalink="https://evelyngeorneys.com/2023/01/06/geology-word-of-the-week-k-is-for-karst/facebook_1672969742822_7016943684200478746/" data-orig-file="https://evelyngeorneys.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/e7e1b-facebook_1672969742822_7016943684200478746.jpg" data-orig-size="720,960" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="facebook_1672969742822_7016943684200478746" data-image-description="&lt;p&gt;Gorgeous speleothems at Howes Caverns, New York State. Picture by myself. &lt;/p&gt;
